    {
      "text": "A 72-year-old male presents with a 2-day history of progressive abdominal distension, constipation, and colicky pain. He has a history of chronic constipation and has been bedridden for the past few months due to a hip fracture. On examination, his abdomen is distended and tympanic, with mild tenderness. Abdominal guarding and rigidity not observed. X-ray of the abdomen is shown below. Which of the following factors does not predispose to this condition?",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Chronic constipation with laxative abuse",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Anticholinergic drugs",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Mentally-retarded individuals",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Short pelvic mesocolon",
          "correct": true
        }
      ],
      "correct_answer": "D. Short pelvic mesocolon",
